<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-302-352  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 302 352.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 2 1990 n294 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Transmit it to the IRS. (Internal Revenue Service) (electronicfilings)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Internal Revenue Service anticipates significant growth inthe number of electronic income tax filings it will receive forthe 1989 tax period.andP;  Companies involved in tax preparations, suchas InstaTax Inc and H and R Block Inc, report that it takes fiveto eight weeks to process a paper filing and only about half thatamount of time to process the same material electronically.andP;  Theuse of electronic filing also reduces the cost of filings fromabout 75 cents per filing to about 3 cents per filing.andP;  By lateMar 1990, the IRS had received about 3.6 million electronicfilings for 1989.andP;  Third-party tax preparers need to use the IBM3780 bisynchronous communications protocol in order to communicatewith the IRS's IBM Series/1 minicomputers.andP;  They also requiremodems with a capacity of 4,800-bps.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   H and R Block Inc. (data processing)InstaTax Inc. (data processing).andO;Topic:     United States. Internal Revenue ServiceAutomationElectronic FilingIncome TaxCost of CommunicationsCommunications EquipmentTax Preparation.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Number of income tax returns filed electronically. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>